article.description: Epiphanny Prince scored 29 points, including going 12-for-12 from the free throw line, to help No. 23 Rutgers snap a three-game losing streak with a 60-51 victory over Villanova on Wednesday night.
article.headline: Prince scores 29, including 12 free throws in Rutgers' victory
article.linkText: Prince perfect from foul line in Rutgers' victory
article.story:
VILLANOVA, Pa. -- Epiphanny Prince scored 29 points, including going 12-for-12 from the free throw line, to help No. 23 Rutgers snap a three-game losing streak with a 60-51 victory over Villanova on Wednesday night.

Khadijah Rushdan added 10 rebounds and Kia Vaughn had nine points and eight boards for the Scarlet Knights (9-5, 1-2 Big East), who entered with losses in their first two conference games for the first time since joining the Big East in the 1995-96 season.

Rutgers beat the Wildcats for the seventh straight time.

Laura Kurz scored 14 of her 19 points in the second half, and Lisa Karcic added 15 for Villanova (9-7, 1-2). It was Villanova's second loss against a ranked team this season. The Wildcats lost 62-57 to then sixth-ranked Baylor on Nov. 28 in the Paradise Jam Classic in St. Thomas.

Rutgers led by as many as 14 points in the first half and held a 32-23 advantage at halftime.

Villanova went on a 23-13 run, and consecutive 3-pointers by Kurz and Heather Scanlon gave the Wildcats a 46-45 lead with 7:17 remaining.

Prince made a driving layup that put Rutgers ahead 51-48, but Karcic responded with a 3-pointer that tied the game at 51 with 3:35 left.

Prince came right back with a 3-pointer, Brittany Ray hit a short jumper from the wing and the Scarlet Knights scored the final nine points of the game to seal the win.

Rutgers coach C. Vivian Stringer didn't make her first substitution until replacing Nikki Speed with Brooklyn Pope with 7:42 remaining in regulation.
